<author><name><![CDATA[TmEE]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-10-12T19:14:53-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-10-12T19:14:53-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134956#p134956</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134956#p134956"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Why is the SNES on screen color pallete so small?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134956#p134956"><![CDATA[
The hardware actually differentiates sprite and BG colors, but you need external RAMDAC to use that, and some arcade boards that use the MD VDP actually do it. You can also use Shadow/highlight status bits to add more palettes. The digital color bus must be explicitly enabled by software though and it is also only present on the non-integrated version of the VDP.<br />I imagine all the limits come from the SMS compatibility, that stuff is almost entirely incompatible with how MD side works, only same thing is the register access and that's basically it. Cut the SMS stuff and there's plenty of realestate for the extra CRAM and DAC bits.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3483">TmEE</a> — Sun Oct 12, 2014 7:14 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
