<author><name><![CDATA[ccovell]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-10-05T16:39:45-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-10-05T16:39:45-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134646#p134646</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134646#p134646"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Why is the SNES on screen color pallete so small?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134646#p134646"><![CDATA[
Consider yourself lucky the SNES even has a pure 256-colour mode at all.  The majority of arcade &amp; console games in the '80s had 4-bit character graphics with 16 colours per tile -- Namco System 1 in the arcade being a notable exception -- the main difference between all the systems being how many total tile palettes they had (The SMS: 2; SNES: 8 (for BG); Turbo: 16, etc.)<br /><br />Plus the SFC was designed in 1986-87, so it's about at parity with the latest console tech at that time.  Nintendo didn't update much (except for the Main RAM capacity) between that time and the SFC's launch in 1990.  That's the bigger crime.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=355">ccovell</a> — Sun Oct 05, 2014 4:39 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
