<title type="html"><![CDATA[Why is the SNES on screen color pallete so small?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11897&amp;p=134637#p134637"><![CDATA[
Although there probably isn't an exact reason, I really just do not understand why the SNES has a huge 32,768 color master palette and has only 256 colors to choose from. Unless there are two nearly identical colors are side by side, which there probably won't be 256 colors, it is really hard to see a difference in color. Even the Turbografx could display 512 colors at once, even if it didn't have nearly as much color fidelity. Would it really have cost that much more money just to add another 512 bytes of cgram? It would seem more wise just to take some memory from the main ram or vram and turn it into cgram, although I'm sure it wouldn't be as simple as that. Sorry for the dumb post. Oh, by the way, I already know that the Sega Genesis had it way worse with only 64 colors (how did anyone manage with that?  <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_eek.gif" alt=":shock:" title="Shocked" />).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=6683">Espozo</a> — Sun Oct 05, 2014 2:41 pm</p><hr />
